---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '../../components/sections/PageHeader.astro';
import RelatedContent from '../../components/sections/RelatedContent.astro';
import CTABand from '../../components/sections/CTABand.astro';
import { buildBreadcrumbSchema, buildArticleSchema } from '../../lib/schema';

const breadcrumb = buildBreadcrumbSchema([
  { name: 'Home', url: '/' },
  { name: 'Blog', url: '/blog' },
  { name: 'Poly bag thickness guide', url: '/blog/poly-bag-thickness-guide' }
]);
const article = buildArticleSchema({
  title: 'Poly bag thickness — when 1.5 mil is enough and when you need 4',
  description: 'Practical guide to polybag gauges from 1.0 mil to 6.0 mil. Match thickness to product weight, edge sharpness, and stacking pattern.',
  url: '/blog/poly-bag-thickness-guide',
  datePublished: '2026-06-02',
  author: 'Apex Packaging Solutions'
});
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Poly Bag Thickness Guide — Choosing the Right Mil Gauge"
  description="Practical guide to polybag gauges from 1.0 mil to 6.0 mil. Match thickness to product weight, edge sharpness, and stacking pattern."
  image="/images/blog/compostable-vs-pcr-polybags-generated.png"
  schemaBlocks={[breadcrumb, article]}
>
  <PageHeader
    eyebrow="Knowledge base · Polybags"
    heading="Poly bag thickness — when 1.5 mil is enough and when you need 4."
    lead="Polybag thickness ('mil') is the most common spec procurement teams get wrong — usually over-specifying, which doubles the bag cost for no real protection benefit."
    imageSrc="/images/blog/compostable-vs-pcr-polybags-generated.png"
    imageAlt="High-resolution Apex Packaging polybag and flexible packaging banner."
  />
  <section class="py-12 md:py-20">
    <div class="container max-w-default prose-apex">
      <h2>What "mil" actually measures</h2>
      <p>One mil = one one-thousandth of an inch (0.001"). A 1.0 mil bag is half as thick as a 2.0 mil bag. The thickness affects:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Puncture resistance</strong> — higher mil resists sharp edges and corners.</li>
        <li><strong>Tear strength</strong> — higher mil resists tear propagation.</li>
        <li><strong>Stretch</strong> — lower mil stretches more under load.</li>
        <li><strong>Cost</strong> — material cost scales roughly linearly with mil.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Thickness by use case</h2>
      <h3>0.5 – 1.0 mil — light retail and produce</h3>
      <p>Wicketed produce bags, light garment bags, retail point-of-sale bags. Use only for soft, light items with no sharp edges.</p>
      <h3>1.0 – 1.5 mil — light shipping</h3>
      <p>General light retail and e-commerce. Apparel, soft goods, light accessories.</p>
      <h3>1.5 – 2.0 mil — standard shipping</h3>
      <p>Most general-purpose shipping bags for products without sharp edges. Auto parts (smooth), small electronics in inner packaging, dry goods.</p>
      <h3>2.0 – 3.0 mil — moderate-weight shipping</h3>
      <p>Heavier products, items with mild edges, moderate stacking. Common for hardware, fasteners, food packaging.</p>
      <h3>3.0 – 4.0 mil — heavy goods and industrial</h3>
      <p>Heavy parts, palletized small items, mattress overwrap, products with sharp corners.</p>
      <h3>4.0 – 6.0 mil — premium protection and large items</h3>
      <p>Furniture overwrap, mattress bags, large industrial parts, applications with stacking pressure or rough handling.</p>

      <h2>When higher isn't better</h2>
      <p>Common over-spec scenarios where 4 mil is bought but 2 mil would have worked:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Smooth-edged products under 5 lb being palletized — 2 mil is fine.</li>
        <li>Apparel and soft goods — 1.5 mil is usually plenty.</li>
        <li>Small electronics in their own box — the bag just needs to be a dust barrier, 1.5–2 mil is fine.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Material matters as much as thickness</h2>
      <p>A 2 mil LLDPE bag is roughly as strong as a 3 mil LDPE bag in puncture resistance.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>LDPE</strong> — flexible, low cost, lower strength per mil.</li>
        <li><strong>LLDPE</strong> — better puncture and tear at lower mil. Default for industrial.</li>
        <li><strong>HDPE</strong> — stiffer, higher strength, lower clarity.</li>
        <li><strong>MDPE</strong> — middle ground.</li>
        <li><strong>Anti-static (pink LDPE)</strong> — for electronics; thickness as needed for handling.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>If you're choosing between higher LDPE mil and lower LLDPE mil, LLDPE almost always wins on cost per unit of strength.</p>

      <h2>A practical specification approach</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Product weight</strong> — under 5 lb (light), 5–25 lb (medium), 25+ lb (heavy).</li>
        <li><strong>Edge sharpness</strong> — smooth (no upgrade), moderate (1 mil up), sharp (2 mil up).</li>
        <li><strong>Handling environment</strong> — gentle (no upgrade), parcel/LTL (1 mil up), bulk truck or hand-tossed (2 mil up).</li>
        <li>Sum the upgrades against your starting mil for the weight class.</li>
      </ol>
      <p>Example: a 12 lb metal fitting going LTL. Start at 2 mil (medium weight). +2 for sharp edges. +1 for LTL handling. Spec at 5 mil — or step to LLDPE at 3 mil to save cost.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
  <RelatedContent items={[
    { title:'Polybags service', href:'/services/polybags', description:'All bag types, gauges, and print options.' },
    { title:'ECT-32 vs ECT-44', href:'/blog/ect-explained', description:'Sister guide on corrugated strength.' },
    { title:'Sustainability', href:'/sustainability', description:'PCR and compostable polybag options.' }
  ]} />
  <CTABand
    heading="Not sure on gauge?"
    lead="Send your product weight, edge profile, and freight environment. Apex specs the right material and gauge."
    primaryCta={{ label: 'Ask Apex', href: '/contact' }}
  />
</BaseLayout>
